dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2015 to 2030 for the national, and first- and second-order administrative division levels of Tanzania were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Tanzania for 2015-2030 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Tanzania's second-order administrative divisions: 195 districts as of the 2012 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the U.S. State Department had 194 polygons and matched the current second-order administrative division subnational structure of Tanzania after several changes to the subnational boundaries by USCB staff: (1) Two polygons were added by USCB staff representing the portions of Lake Victoria and Lake Tanganyika that fall within the international boundary of Tanzania. (2) The original Magharibi polygon was split by USCB staff into Magharibi A and Magharibi B.
These changes resulted in a shapefile with 197 polygons, one for each of Tanzania's second-order administrative divisions (168 districts) as reported by the Tanzania National Bureau of Statistics in the 2012 census, one for each of 27 new districts formed after the census, one for Lake Victoria, and one for Lake Tanganyika. Finally, the U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues.
NOTE After the 2012 census, 27 new districts were created by splitting from previously existing districts, as noted in the USCBCMNT field. Original 2002 population totals and 2012 age and sex census data for these areas were split by USCB staff proportionally, according to third-level administrative population totals by sex within each of the new areas.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2015-2030 population estimates for Tanzania's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Tanzania_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_uscb_feb2022.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEO_MATCH." (2) The Excel table "Tanzania_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_508_uscb_feb2022.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2015-2030 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
